WEBVTT

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:06.720
So we learned the autoenccoders and we

00:00:03.520 --> 00:00:09.760
discussed how they can handle sequences.

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:13.440
For example, a sentence like hello world

00:00:09.760 --> 00:00:16.560
can be encoded to a fixed size latent

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:19.039
and then decoded to the translated let's

00:00:16.560 --> 00:00:21.279
say in French. So like we discussed this

00:00:19.039 --> 00:00:24.080
is a maybe a preliminary solution

00:00:21.279 --> 00:00:26.960
because it's not really the most

00:00:24.080 --> 00:00:30.000
efficient especially if we go to longer

00:00:26.960 --> 00:00:33.200
sentences or large text.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:35.760
So if we have varying lengths of u

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:38.399
sequences we are encoding all of them to

00:00:35.760 --> 00:00:40.399
a fixed size latent.

00:00:38.399 --> 00:00:44.320
For example, if we have a fiveword

00:00:40.399 --> 00:00:47.760
tweet, we encode to the same Z as in a

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:50.960
500word essay or a entire book. They all

00:00:47.760 --> 00:00:52.960
have the same Z. Which means that if the

00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:56.239
length of the sequence is getting

00:00:52.960 --> 00:00:59.359
larger, the amount of information that Z

00:00:56.239 --> 00:01:02.399
can share with each one of the tokens

00:00:59.359 --> 00:01:05.439
uh will be reduced. And at some point if

00:01:02.399 --> 00:01:08.000
the length of the sequence goes to a

00:01:05.439 --> 00:01:10.159
let's say very large value the

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:13.439
information that Z can capture from each

00:01:10.159 --> 00:01:15.920
one of these tokens gets goes to zero.

00:01:13.439 --> 00:01:20.400
Second problem is the autoenccoders

00:01:15.920 --> 00:01:22.799
treat inputs as of as a bag of features.

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:24.720
They don't really naturally preserve the

00:01:22.799 --> 00:01:27.200
order. For example, consider these two

00:01:24.720 --> 00:01:30.479
inputs and the encoder basically treat

00:01:27.200 --> 00:01:32.640
them similarly. There's no explicit

00:01:30.479 --> 00:01:35.119
positional encoding meaning that the

00:01:32.640 --> 00:01:37.840
order is not preserved but the order we

00:01:35.119 --> 00:01:39.759
know matter at least in language these

00:01:37.840 --> 00:01:42.000
two sentences are not the same. The

00:01:39.759 --> 00:01:45.600
third problem is we resolve the variable

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:48.799
length uh issue with padding which then

00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:51.680
wastes a lot of computation and then

00:01:48.799 --> 00:01:54.960
model learns patterns about where the

00:01:51.680 --> 00:01:58.159
real data ends are not real and it's

00:01:54.960 --> 00:02:00.640
sparious. Moreover, we are really not

00:01:58.159 --> 00:02:04.640
capitalizing on batch efficiency because

00:02:00.640 --> 00:02:07.280
we are giving one sequence at a time and

00:02:04.640 --> 00:02:10.080
within the sequence we may have outliers

00:02:07.280 --> 00:02:12.160
that can destroy really the benefits of

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:14.640
the averaging. We had another option

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:17.280
which was truncating the sequence to a

00:02:14.640 --> 00:02:19.840
fixed length. But here again we will

00:02:17.280 --> 00:02:24.080
have some issues with the information uh

00:02:19.840 --> 00:02:27.360
that will be lost. And then also if some

00:02:24.080 --> 00:02:30.879
sequences are just naturally long uh we

00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:32.720
are not able to learn for them because

00:02:30.879 --> 00:02:35.920
the autoenccoder basically feed

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:38.560
everything at once. One last issue is uh

00:02:35.920 --> 00:02:41.120
there is no natural chunking meaning

00:02:38.560 --> 00:02:44.160
that if the data comes in a se in a

00:02:41.120 --> 00:02:46.879
streaming sense uh we should wait until

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:48.959
the entire sequence ends and then feed

00:02:46.879 --> 00:02:51.280
it to the auto autoenccoder. This is

00:02:48.959 --> 00:02:54.560
really undesirable because sometimes we

00:02:51.280 --> 00:02:57.040
want for example live translation and we

00:02:54.560 --> 00:03:00.800
want something that can handle it and

00:02:57.040 --> 00:03:03.040
give us the output so far for example

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:05.280
until we have the sequence then when

00:03:03.040 --> 00:03:08.480
there is an addition to the sequence the

00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:11.599
the output can be uh updated. So here we

00:03:08.480 --> 00:03:14.560
introduce the RNN the recurrent neural

00:03:11.599 --> 00:03:16.879
network architectures that deals with

00:03:14.560 --> 00:03:19.040
all of these issues that we discussed.

